									Steven Lykowski on August 20, 2015
									                                

                                
									Reply ↓                                


                            Hi James,
I am beginning the production process for my first KS game. My manufacturer is asking me to sign a Letter of Authorization and an invoice before we begin production.  Neither of these provide me any guarantees…one gives them permission to print my game and the other just obliges me to pay them.  Isn’t there also supposed to be a manufacturing contract with very specific terms that gives me guarantees on my end?  
Thanks.

                        
                    
                    


                
                
                        
                        
							
                        
                    
                    
                    
                        
                            
									James Mathe on August 23, 2015
									                                

                                
									Reply ↓                                


                            You’ll be surprised how little paperwork they want to do and as long as you get a sample of what you want FIRST then it’s usually not a big issue. Most of the China factories are honestly trying to just make a buck. They rarely just rip people off – they have a rep to worry about. They do however make many stupid mistakes or miscommunications on details. So make sure you have as complete of a sample copy as you can get before you send over the big downpayment – then make sure you get a sample before the final payment.

                        
                    
                    


                
                
                        
                        
							
                        
                    
                    
                    
                        
                            
									Steven Lykowski on August 24, 2015
									                                

                                
									Reply ↓                                


                            Good to know.  I’ve been reading a lot on how China rarely cares about contracts and usually focuses on relationships and reputation, like you mentioned.  From a normal business standpoint I find that disconcerting though.  Thankfully I was able to squeeze an additional contract out of them.
Do all manufacturers send out complete samples before the down payment?  Mine does not.

                        
                    
                    


                
                
                        
                        
							
                        
                    
                    
                    
                        
                            
									James Mathe on August 24, 2015
									                                

                                
									                                


                            No. Most can supply you with samples of other games. But once you sign the contract and pay the 50% down, you can make sure they send you at the very least a white-box version of the game (one without printing done) and a sample that was laser printed and hand assembled. That way you know you got all your ducks in a row.

                        
                    
                    


                



                
                
                        
                        
							
                        
                    
                    
                    
                        
                            
									Steven Lykowski on October 8, 2015
									                                

                                
									Reply ↓                                


                            I received a laser-print sample. Should I also be receiving a shrinkwrapped mass production copy before they hit the green light? Or at least full-size proof sheets?  Thanks.

                        
                    
                    


                
                
                        
                        
							
                        
                    
                    
                    
                        
                            
									James Mathe on October 8, 2015
									                                

                                
									Reply ↓                                


                            No the MPC is usually a first off the line sent to you before they finish assembling all your games – meaning everything is probably already printed and ready to be put together and shipped. If you find something wrong with the MPC that means they’ll have to remake some element of your game – it’s costly but it’s your last chance for change before they ship the game.  You should get full size proof sheets to color check though before anything is too far along.

                        
                    
                    


                

                
                
                        
                        
							
                        
                    
                    
                    
                        
                            
									Steven Lykowski on October 23, 2015
									                                

                                
									Reply ↓                                


                            If I want to color-check the completed cards on their offset printer, they are asking for $2k to print out all 8 plates which seems absurd (or I can ask to see just 1 plate for $220).  I just thought there was some way to check the totally completed game before mass production begins.

                        
                    
                    


                
                
                        
                        
							
                        
                    
                    
                    
                        
                            
									James Mathe on October 25, 2015
									                                

                                
									Reply ↓                                


                            Different printers do different things and build in different costs. Seems like you might have went to a super cheap quote that didn’t allow for any mailing of physical samples. The shipping alone can be $80-200 for samples as they have to send them Fedex.  But $2k – no that’s not reasonable in the slightest. I don’t know a huge amount about how this is done, but it’s possible that our color checks are done not on the offset printer but a high quality laser and you approve it and then they make their offset printer match it. Cause firing up an offset printer and getting all the coloring set and such takes a lot of time and ink and paper as they can’t just print a couple sheets, they have to print huge amounts as the printer runs fast.  So maybe it’s just a matter of explaining what you really need – which is just a sample you can approve the color on and it doesn’t have to actually be from their actual offset printer.

                        
                    
                    


                

                
                
                        
                        
							
                        
                    
                    
                    
                        
                            
